<subSubSection id="F49041CF94D23C09C1365BDF4B8BDFAD" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="E02C003E77D3DD8519774D1E532DFB13" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F7C0718F4028528F090E2730041F8D52" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
The word 
<taxonomicName id="E834A2DCE88D99947AAC269549BA53DE" authorityName="Vujic, Likov &amp; Radenkovic" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Merodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="nigropunctum" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigropunctum">
<emphasis id="6BB32538AFC458F245DE3D9738B090D6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">nigropunctum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is derived from the Latin words 
<emphasis id="41FBA1AF886A480828E8B49A391267B1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">niger</emphasis>
(black, dark whitish) and 
<emphasis id="94FE4ADC092B4AB76F08E5AAA2641F6F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">punctum</emphasis>
(dot/spot) referring to the dark macula on the wing as an important diagnostic character of this new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5CB65EEEE244898009134D10128B8682" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="distribution">
